{{distinguish|Qasr al-Banat|Qasr el Banat|Qasr el Banat, Lebanon}}
{{Infobox ancient site |name = Gasr Banat |native_name = |alternate_name = |image =Qasr banat.JPG |alt = |caption = |map_type = Libya |map_alt = |map_size = |location = [[Libya]] |region = |coordinates = {{coord|31.461836|14.704529|display=inline}} |type = [[Fort]] |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder = |material = |built = |abandoned = |epochs = [[Ancient Rome]] |cultures = |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = |archaeologists = [[Graeme Barker]] |condition = |ownership = |management = |public_access = |website = |notes = }} '''Gasr Banat''' or '''Gasr Isawi''' is an archaeological site in [[Libya]] and the location of an [[Ancient Roman]] [[centenarium]] or "perched" [[oppidum]]. The area is also used as a semi-permanent camp for [[nomads]].<ref name="Mattingly1995">{{cite book|author=David Mattingly|title=Tripolitania|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cYze_G2ApWoC&pg=PP10|accessdate=31 October 2012|date=5 February 1995|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-7134-5742-1|pages=10–}}</ref><ref name="BarkerJones1982">{{cite book|author1=Graeme Barker|author2=Barri Jones|title=The UNESCO Libyan valleys survey 1979-1981: palaeoeconomy and environmental archaeology in the pre-desert|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9GtwAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=31 October 2012|year=1982|publisher=Society for Libyan Studies|isbn=978-0-9508363-0-0}}</ref><ref name="BarkerSurvey1996">{{cite book|author1=Graeme Barker|author2=Unesco Libyan Valleys Archaeological Survey|title=Farming the Desert: Synthesis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-RcYAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=31 October 2012|year=1996|publisher=UNESCO}}</ref> It was studied by [[Graeme Barker]] in 1984.<ref name="Libyan Studies: Annual Report of the Society for Libyan Studies">{{cite book|title=Libyan Studies: Annual Report of the Society for Libyan Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VXFwAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=31 October 2012|year=1986|publisher=The Society}}</ref> Evidence from [[pottery]] found around the site suggests the date of construction was in the third century CE.<ref name="Mattingly1995"/>
The centenarium has a striking resemblance to one in [[Gherait esh-Shergia]] north of [[Wadi Nefud]]. There is an ancient temple-type [[mausoleum]] dating to the same period as the centenarium in the valley, which contains a burial chamber decorated with [[fish]]. There are also remains of a Roman [[quarry]] and dams in the nearby [[wadi]].<ref>Erwin Ruprechtsberger, Die römische Limeszone in Tripolitanien und der Kyrenaika, Tunesien - Libyen (1993 Aalen; Limes Museum)</ref>
