{{about-otherpeople|the Scottish lawyer||George Mackenzie (disambiguation)}} [[File:George MacKenzie.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Sir George Mackenzie.]] '''Sir George Mackenzie of Rosehaugh''' (1636/1638–1691) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] lawyer, [[Lord Advocate]], [[essayist]] and legal writer.<ref>The exact year of his birth is uncertain: his biography in the [[Dictionary of National Biography]] identifies the year as 1636, as does the biography published in the folio edition of his works (1716-1722), but he himself in his own work, ''The Religious Stoic'', declared in 1663 that he was not yet 25 {{harv|Lang|1909|p=22}}. "[He was born] either in 1636, as most sources assert, or in 1638, as his own works suggest" {{harv|Jackson|2007}}.</ref>
==Early life== Mackenzie, who was born in [[Dundee]], was the son of Sir Simon Mackenzie of [[Lochslin]] (died c. 1666) and Elizabeth Bruce, daughter of the Reverend Peter Bruce, minister of St Leonard's, and Principal of St Leonard's Hall in the University of St Andrews. He was a grandson of [[Kenneth Mackenzie, 1st Lord Mackenzie of Kintail|Kenneth, Lord Mackenzie of Kintail]] and a nephew of [[George Mackenzie, 2nd Earl of Seaforth]].{{sfn|Lang|1909|p=21}}
He was educated at the [[King's College, Aberdeen|King's College]], [[University of Aberdeen]] (which he entered in 1650), the [[University of St Andrews]], and the [[University of Bourges]] in France.{{sfn|Lang|1909|p=25}}
==Career== [[File:George Mackenzie after Kneller.jpg|thumb|180px|left|Sir George Mackenzie, by [[Godfrey Kneller|Sir Godfrey Kneller]]]] Mackenzie was elected to the [[Faculty of Advocates]] in 1659, and spoke in defence at the trial of [[Archibald Campbell, 1st Marquess of Argyll|Archibald Campbell, Marquis of Argyll]] in 1661.<ref name="Jackson">{{harv|Jackson|2007}}</ref> He acted as [[justice-depute]] from 1661 to 1663, a post that involved him in extensive [[witch trial]]s.<ref name="Jackson"/>
Mackenzie was knighted, and was a member of the Scottish Parliament for the County of Ross from 1669.{{sfn|Lee|1903|p=817}} In 1677 he became [[Lord Advocate]],{{sfn|Cousin|1910}} and a member of the [[Privy Council of Scotland]].{{sfn|Lee|1903|p=817}}
As Lord Advocate he was the [[minister (government)|minister]] responsible for the persecuting policy of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] in Scotland against the Presbyterian [[Covenanter]]s. After the [[Battle of Bothwell Bridge]] in 1679 Mackenzie imprisoned 1,200 Covenanters in a field next to [[Greyfriars Kirkyard]].<ref>The field was later incorporated into Greyfriars Kirkyard and that section is known as the "Covenanters' Prison" {{harv|Scottish Covenanter Memorials Association}}</ref> Some were executed, and hundreds died of maltreatment. His treatment of Covenanters gained him the nickname "Bluidy Mackenzie".{{sfn|Cousin|1910}} It has been argued that both he and [[John Graham of Claverhouse|Claverhouse]] kept to the letter of the law.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Bruce Lenman|author2=J Mackie|title=A History of Scotland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_cvp_njNb2sC&pg=PT315|accessdate=26 February 2013|date=28 February 1991|publisher=Penguin Books Limited|isbn=978-0-14-192756-5|page=315}}</ref> It is unclear whether or not the epithet "Bluidy" is contemporary; it appears in ''[[The Heart of Midlothian]]'' (1818), given to Davie Deans.<ref>{{cite book|author=Andrew Lang|title=Sir George MacKenzie: King's Advocate, of Rosehaugh, His Life and Times 1636(?)-1691|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HojdEeuOZo0C&pg=PA2|accessdate=26 February 2013|date=1 November 2005|publisher=The Lawbook Exchange, Ltd.|isbn=978-1-58477-616-1|page=2}}</ref> The language of blood prevails in the published testimony of Marion Harvey, hanged in 1681, who calls her blood onto Mackenzie: ""that excommunicate tyrant, George Mackenzie, the advocate", among others.<ref name="Christ1794">{{cite book|title=A cloud of witnesses, for the royal prerogatives of Jesus Christ: or, The last speeches and testimonies of those who have suffered for the truth in Scotland, since 1680|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKAHAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA99|accessdate=26 February 2013|year=1794|page=99}}</ref> [[File:Mackenzie mausoleum, Greyfriars.JPG|thumb|180px|Mackenzie mausoleum in Greyfriars, Edinburgh]] Mackenzie resigned for a short time in 1686, taking up office again in 1688.{{sfn|Lee|1903|p=817}} He opposed the dethronement of [[James II of England|James II]], and to escape the consequences he retired from public life.{{sfn|Lee|1903|p=817}}
==Last years== Mackenzie retired at the [[Glorious Revolution]] to [[Oxford]]. In London on 9 March 1690 he dined with [[William Lloyd (bishop of Worcester)|William Lloyd]] and [[John Evelyn]], two literary opponents from the past.<ref>{{cite book|author=John Evelyn|title=Diary and correspondence of John Evelyn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p1U7AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA317|accessdate=26 February 2013|year=1870|publisher=Bell and Daldy|page=317}}</ref> He died at [[Westminster]] on 8 May 1691 and is buried in [[Greyfriars Kirkyard]] in [[Edinburgh]], his mausoleum being designed by [[James Smith (architect)|James Smith]].{{sfn|Cousin|1910}}
==Works== In private life Mackenzie was a cultivated and learned gentleman with literary tendencies. He published in 1660 ''Aretina'', which has been called the first [[Novel in Scotland|Scottish novel]].<ref name="Mackenzie2005">{{cite book|author=George Mackenzie|title=The Laws And Customes Of Scotland, In Matters Criminal: Wherein To Be Seen How The Civil Law, And The Laws And Customs Of Other Nations Do Agree With, And Supply Ours|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kjp58dFZEuMC&pg=PR3|accessdate=26 February 2013|date=1 October 2005|publisher=The Lawbook Exchange, Ltd.|isbn=978-1-58477-605-5|pages=iii note 4.}}</ref> He is remembered as the author of various graceful [[essay]]s. A contemporary antiquarian, [[Alexander Nisbet]], calls him "learned" and "renowned".<ref>{{cite book|title=A System of Heraldry|date=1816|volume=1|pages=152 & 329|author=Alexander Nisbet|location=Edinburgh|publisher=William Blackwood}}</ref>
Mackenzie wrote legal, political, and antiquarian books, including:
[[File:Title page of Mackenzie's Vindication, 1691.JPG|thumb|180px|Title page of Mackenzie's 'Vindication', published in 1691]]
*''The Science of Heraldry, Treated as a Part of the Civil Law of Nations: Wherein Reasons are Given for its Principles, and Etymologies of its Harder Terms'' (1680); *''Institutions of the Law of Scotland'' (1684); *''Jus Regium: Or the Just and Solid Foundations of Monarchy in General, and More Especially of the Monarchy of Scotland: Maintain'd Against Buchannan, Naphtali, Dolman, Milton, &c.'' (1684), a major royalist tract;<ref>{{cite book|author=George Mackenzie|title=Jus Regium: Or the Just and Solid Foundations of Monarchy in General, and More Especially of the Monarchy of Scotland: Maintain'd Against Buchannan, Naphtali, Dolman, Milton, &c. By Sir George Mackenzie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5O_OtgAACAAJ|accessdate=26 February 2013|year=1684|publisher=heir of Andrew Anderson}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Kenneth G. C. Reid|author2=Reinhard Zimmerman|title=A History of Private Law in Scotland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mPGAcjrar4oC&pg=PA106|accessdate=26 February 2013|year=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-826778-2|page=106}}</ref> * ''A Vindication of the Government in Scotland'' (1691); *''Antiquity of the Royal Line of Scotland'' (1686); *''Memoirs of the Affairs of Scotland from the Restoration of Charles II'' (1821).
Mackenzie took part in the [[Midlothian]] trials for [[witchcraft]] in 1661, and defended the alleged witch Maevia.<ref>{{cite book|author=Darren Oldridge|title=The Witchcraft Reader|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1sCSnTiZT1sC&pg=PA219|accessdate=26 February 2013|year=2002|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-21492-6|page=219}}</ref> He later wrote at length of his experience with witchcraft trials.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alex Sutherland|title=The Brahan Seer: The Making of a Legend|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uwT00nyEPSkC&pg=PA61|accessdate=26 February 2013|date=7 January 2009|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=978-3-03911-868-7|page=61}}</ref> He did not endorse the sceptical position, but stated that witches were fewer than common belief made out.<ref>{{cite book|author=Julian Goodare|title=The Scottish Witch-Hunt in Context|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W50K_7HmZNIC&pg=PA168|accessdate=26 February 2013|date=21 September 2002|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=978-0-7190-6024-3|page=168}}</ref> He attributed confessions to the use of torture.<ref name="Black2003">{{cite book|author=George Fraser Black|title=Calendar of Cases of Witchcraft in Scotland 1510 to 1727|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t5UktwEHx1oC&pg=PA16|accessdate=26 February 2013|date=1 May 2003|publisher=Kessinger Publishing|isbn=978-0-7661-5838-2|page=16}}</ref>
His ''Laws and Customs of Scotland in Matters Criminal'' (1678) was the first textbook of [[Scottish criminal law]].<ref name="Broadie2010">{{cite book|author=Alexander Broadie|title=The Scottish Enlightenment Reader|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A4H0H3y_9oIC&pg=PA12|accessdate=26 February 2013|date=1 July 2010|publisher=Canongate Books|isbn=978-1-84767-573-6|page=12}}</ref> In it Mackenzie defended the use of [[judicial torture]] in Scotland as legal. He said it was seldom used.<ref name="Smout">{{cite book|author=T C Smout|title=Anglo-Scottish Relations from 1603 to 1900|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LpPDNU8S5oMC&pg=PA79|accessdate=26 February 2013|date=22 December 2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-726330-3|pages=79–8}}</ref> In the aftermath of the [[Rye House Plot]] Charles II authorised the use of torture against [[William Spence (conspirator)|William Spence]], secretary to [[Archibald Campbell, 9th Earl of Argyll|Archibald, Earl of Agyll]], who was moved to Scotland. The Scottish privy council was reluctant, but eventually went beyond Scottish law in torturing Spence.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=67376|title=Spence, William|first=Tim|last=Harris}}</ref> Mackenzie visited [[William Carstares]] in prison in London, caught up in the same investigation, to warn him of the consequences of stubborn behaviour under questioning.<ref name="Smout"/>
Other works were:<ref>{{cite book|author=Daniela Havenstein|title=Democratizing Sir Thomas Browne: Religio Medici and Its Imitations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DRby35YgOdYC&pg=PA30|accessdate=26 February 2013|year=1999|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-818626-7|page=30}}</ref>
*''Religio Stoici'' (1663); *''A Moral Essay preferring Solitude to Public Employment'' (1665); *''Moral Gallantry'' (1667); and *''The Moral History of Frugality'' (1691).
==Legacy== Mackenzie was the founder of the [[Advocates Library]] in [[Edinburgh]]. His inaugural oration there is dated 15 March 1689, so just before his departure south; but the evidence is that the oration was written some years before, and the library itself was operational from the early 1680s.<ref>Cadell and Matheson, p. 1.</ref> The initiative followed Mackenzie's appointment as [[Dean of the Faculty of Advocates]], in 1682.<ref>{{cite book|author=Clare Jackson|title=Restoration Scotland, 1660-1690: Royalist Politics, Religion and Ideas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IUcT221m02sC&pg=PA27|accessdate=26 February 2013|year=2003|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=978-0-85115-930-0|page=27}}</ref>
==Family== In 1662 Mackenzie married Elizabeth, daughter of John Dickson of Hartree, one of the Senators of the [[College of Justice]].<ref name="Jackson"/> They had:{{sfn|Mackenzie|1879|p=279}} *John (died young) *Simon (died young) *George (died young) *Agnes, who married [[James Stuart, 1st Earl of Bute|James Stuart]], later 1st [[Earl of Bute]] *Elizabeth, who married first Sir Archibald Cockburn of Langton and secondly the Hon Sir James [[Mackenzie Baronets|Mackenzie of Royston]], Bt. His first wife died not later than 1667-1668 and in 1670 he married secondly Margaret, daughter of Haliburton of Pitcur.{{sfn|Lang|1909|p=77,78}} They had a son and two daughters:{{sfn|Mackenzie|1879|p=279}} *George, who married but died, without male issue, before his father *Anne, who married Sir William Dick of Prestonfield *Elizabeth, who married Sir John Stuart of Grandtully
